    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Defending Napster To the Editor:</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Garrett letter on Aug 31 article questions whether people who spread bogus MP3 files on Napster to protect copyright holders got permission to use copyrighted characters for stunt; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>John Fix 3rd and Michael Fix say they are striking a blow for copyright holders by spreading bogus MP3 files that they label with the names of popular songs. The files include audio clips of Charlie Brown saying, ''Congratulations,'' and a clip of Yosemite Sam saying, ''Looks like you goofed up somewhere.'' You neglected to mention whether the Fix brothers obtained permission from the estate of Charles Schulz and from Warner Brothers for the appropriation of those (copyrighted) characters in this stunt.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL GARRETT  New York</p>
      </block>
